1. Introduction

This report presents an individual analysis of the widely-used credit card client dataset, which contains information on users’ demographics, credit history, and payment behavior. The main goal of the task is to develop predictive models that can identify clients who are likely to default on their credit card payments in the upcoming month.

To achieve this, I apply both logistic regression and random forest classifiers—focusing not just on prediction accuracy but also on interpretability. Special attention is given to feature engineering and evaluation metrics to ensure the models are both effective and explainable.

This kind of analysis is highly relevant in real-world financial settings, where understanding default risk helps institutions minimize losses and make better lending decisions.

Workflow for The Analysis :

2. Data Description: Default of Credit Card Clients

Observations: 30,000 credit card clients
Time Period: April 2005 to September 2005
Target Variable:
- customer_default: Binary (1 = default, 0 = no default)

Predictor Variables:

1. Demographic & Credit Info

  • limit_bal: Credit limit (NT dollar)
  • sex: Gender (1 = male, 2 = female)
  • education: Education level (1 = grad school, 2 = university, 3 = high school, 4 = others)
  • marriage: Marital status (1 = married, 2 = single, 3 = others)
  • age: Age (years)

2. Payment History (Past 6 Months)

  • pay_1 to pay_6: Repayment status for September 2005 (pay_1) to April 2005 (pay_6)
    • Scale:
      • -1 = Pay duly
      • 0 = No consumption
      • 1 = 1-month delay, …, 9 = 9+ months delay

3. Bill Statements (NT dollar)

  • bill_amt1 to bill_amt6: Bill amount for September 2005 (bill_amt1) to April 2005 (bill_amt6)

4. Payment Amounts (NT dollar)

  • pay_amt1 to pay_amt6: Amount paid in September 2005 (pay_amt1) to April 2005 (pay_amt6)

Key Notes:

  1. Time Alignment:
    • pay_1/bill_amt1/pay_amt1 = September 2005 (most recent)
    • pay_6/bill_amt6/pay_amt6 = April 2005 (oldest)
  2. Class Imbalance:
    • Default rate ≈ 22% (minority class).

3. Data Cleaning and EDA

Train-Test Split

First of all we separate out 20% of the data as test_data.csv for final testing. We performed all the analysis including EDA or train_data.csv. While doing so, we corrected one mislabeled feature pay_0 to pay_1.

  • There are total 23 predictors and one response (default). [1] “limit_bal” “sex” “education” “marriage” “age” “pay_1”
    [7] “pay_2” “pay_3” “pay_4” “pay_5” “pay_6” “bill_amt1” [13] “bill_amt2” “bill_amt3” “bill_amt4” “bill_amt5” “bill_amt6” “pay_amt1” [19] “pay_amt2” “pay_amt3” “pay_amt4” “pay_amt5” “pay_amt6” “default”

  • For simplicity let’s call pay_1 to pay_6 as pay_vars, bill_amt1 to bill_amt6 as bill_amt_vars and pay_amt1 to pay_amt6 pay_amt_vars.

# Cleaning and renaming categories
df <- df %>%
  mutate(
    # Renaming SEX (1 = Male, 2 = Female)
    sex = factor(sex, levels = c(1, 2), labels = c("male", "female")),
    
    # Cleaning MARRIAGE (merge 0 into 3 as "Others")
    marriage = case_when(
      marriage %in% c(0, 3) ~ "others",
      marriage == 1 ~ "married",
      marriage == 2 ~ "single",
      TRUE ~ "others"
    ),
    
    # Cleaning EDUCATION (merge 0,4,5,6 into "others")
    education = case_when(
      education == 1 ~ "grad School",
      education == 2 ~ "university",
      education == 3 ~ "high School",
      education %in% c(0, 4, 5, 6) ~ "others",
      TRUE ~ "others"
    )
  )

# Verifying the new distributions

Default Rate by Payment Status for Each pay_vars

Scatter Plot Explanation

Observing the Default rate for Continuous Variables

  • Our goal is get set of predictors which are responsible for default, we can easily calculate default rate for the predictors which are ordinal or categorical in nature like pay_vars or marriage but we can’t directly observe or calculate the default rate as function of continuous predictor.
  • To visualize the relationship between default rate and continuous predictor, I have divided the range of predictor in 80 equal sample size bins. Then for each bin, I recorded the median predictor value and default rate of the observations within that bin.
  • Thus each point in the plot is representing each bin (1.25% or 300 observations) and there are near 40 points in each plot.
  • To analyze continuous variables such as bill_amt or pay_amt or limit_bal I have used the auto_plot function from ggplot_helper.R .

Comments

  • From the above plots, we can clearly observe that pay_amt and default rate has -ve correlation.
  • However, this variable is as welll highly right skewed. Do deal with it we need to adopt robust methods while creating logistic regression model.
  • We can see there is an highly influential as well as high leverage point in each plot, which indicates that appox 5% (1200) observations are high leverage and that is enough for a regression line to drag towards them. We must need to truncate these influential observations.
  • In order to do that, we can truncate these 5% observations to the 95% percentile value.
# Enhanced Truncation Function with Verification
truncate_top_outliers <- function(data, var_name, percentile = 0.95) {
  
  # Calculate cutoff
  trunc_value <- quantile(data[[var_name]], probs = percentile, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  # Create new column name
  new_col <- paste0(var_name, "_truncated")
  
  # Apply truncation
  data <- data %>%
    mutate(
      "{new_col}" := ifelse(
        .data[[var_name]] > trunc_value,
        trunc_value,
        .data[[var_name]]
      )
    )
  
  return(data)
}


vars_to_truncate <- paste0("pay_amt", 1:6)
for (var in vars_to_truncate) {
  df <- truncate_top_outliers(df, var)
}

After Truncation of 5% Right Most Observations

4. Feature Engineering (Using Domain Knowledge)

Please Click on show code to see new features and their definition :

1. VARIABLES_DENOTING_THE_WORST_PAYMENT_STATUS_IN_LAST_N_MONTH

payment_history <- df[, paste0("pay_", 1:6)]

# Function to get worst status in last n months
get_worst_status <- function(n) {
  apply(payment_history[, 1:n, drop = FALSE], 1, max)
}

# Creating new variables for n in c(1,2,3,6) months
for (n in c(1,2,3,6)) {
  df[[paste0("worst_status_", n, "m")]] <- get_worst_status(n)
}

2. VARIABLES_DENOTING_IF_PAYMENT_STATUS_GE_1_2_3_OR_5_IN_LAST_1_2_3_OR_6_MONTHS

# Function to check if any status >= x in last n months
status_ge_x <- function(x, n) {
  apply(payment_history[, 1:n, drop = FALSE], 1, function(row) any(row > x))
}

# Creating variables for combinations of x in c(0,1,2) and n in c(1,2,3,6)
for (x in c(0,1,2,3,5)) {
  for (n in c(1,2,3,6)) {
    df[[paste0("status_ge", x, "_last", n, "m")]] <- as.numeric(status_ge_x(x, n))
  }
}

3. COUNT_OF_MONTHS_WITH_DELAYED_PAYMENTS (STATUS >= x)

for (x in c(0,1,2,3,5)) {
  df[[paste0("count_months_ge_", x)]] <- rowSums(df[, paste0("pay_", 1:6)] >= x)
}

4. MONTHS_SINCE_LAST_DELINQUENCY (STATUS >= x)

for (x in c(0,1,2,3,5)) {
  df[[paste0("months_since_delq_ge_", x)]] <- apply(df[, paste0("pay_", 1:6)], 1, function(row) {
    idx <- which(row >= x)
    ifelse(length(idx) > 0, min(idx), 0) 
  })
}

## IF IN LAST 6 MONTHS ONE HAS NEVER DELINQUENT (STATUS >= X)

for (x in c(0,1,2,3,5)) {
  df[[paste0("last6m_never_delq_ge_", x)]] <- apply(df[, paste0("pay_", 1:6)], 1, function(row) {
    idx <- which(row >= x)
    ifelse(length(idx) > 0, 0, 1) 
  })
}

12. CALCULATION OF MONTHLY PAYMENT PROPORTIONS (PAYMENT AMOUNT / BILL AMOUNT)

  ## Convert the 'pay_amt' and 'bill_amt' columns to matrices for calculations
  payments <- as.matrix(df[, paste0("pay_amt", 1:6)])
  bills <- as.matrix(df[, paste0("bill_amt", 1:6)])
  
  ## Calculate the proportion of payments made by dividing payments by bills
  prop_paid_matrix <- payments / bills
  
  ## Handle Inf or NaN values by replacing them with 0
  prop_paid_matrix[is.infinite(prop_paid_matrix) | is.nan(prop_paid_matrix)] <- 0  
  
  ## Set the column names to represent payment percentages for each month
  colnames(prop_paid_matrix) <- c("Sep_paid_pct", "Aug_paid_pct", "Jul_paid_pct", "Jun_paid_pct", "May_paid_pct", "Apr_paid_pct")

13. CALCULATION OF PAYMENT BEHAVIOR METRICS (FULL PAYMENT, LOW PAYMENT, OVERPAYMENT etc.)

  ## Average proportion paid (last 3m/6m)
  df$avg_paid_pct_3m <- rowMeans(prop_paid_matrix[, 1:3], na.rm = TRUE)  # Sep-Aug-Jul
  df$avg_paid_pct_6m <- rowMeans(prop_paid_matrix[, 1:6], na.rm = TRUE)  # Sep-Apr
  
  ## Months with full payment (100%)
  df$months_full_payment <- rowSums(prop_paid_matrix == 1, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  ## Months with minimal payment (<30%)
  df$months_low_payment <- rowSums(prop_paid_matrix < 0.3, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  ## Months with overpayment (>100%)
  df$months_overpayment <- rowSums(prop_paid_matrix > 1, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  ## Worst Payment Ratio
  df$min_paid_pct_6m <- apply(prop_paid_matrix, 1, function(x) {
    if (all(is.na(x))) NA else min(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  })

14. MORE VARIABLES FOR PAYMENT BEHAVIOR

  ## Payment volatility (standard deviation)
  df$paid_pct_volatility <- apply(prop_paid_matrix, 1, sd, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  ## Current payment ratio (most recent month)
  df$current_paid_pct <- prop_paid_matrix[, 1]
  
  ## Months since last underpayment (<90%)
  df$months_since_underpayment <- apply(prop_paid_matrix, 1, function(x) {  
    ifelse(length(which(x < 0.9)) == 0,0,which(x < 0.9)[1]) })
  
  ## Never Underpaid in last 6 months
  df$last6m_never_underpayment <- apply(prop_paid_matrix, 1, function(x) {  
    length(which(x < 0.9)) == 0 })
  
  ## Ever missed payment (0% paid)
  df$ever_missed_payment <- as.numeric(rowSums(prop_paid_matrix == 0, na.rm = TRUE) > 0)

FEATURE EXPLORER

5. Feature Transformation (Modification of New Features)

Assessing the Good and Bad Variables and Creating Final Set of Features Before Modeling

  • We have more than hundred of features now, but we need to consider only those that have some explanatory power.
  • For each variable I observed their relationship with default rate through the scatter plot, and based on the relationship I applied some transformation on the predictor so that, the relationship between Default Rate and predictor is roughly linear. The predictor which shows no relationship has been dropped later and the predictors with good linear relationship after the transformation has been kept.
  • Following code chunk contains all the modification and transformation in the features, that has been done. You can follow feature explorer to understand why I called some variables bad and transformed the others.
# Transformation
CleanTransformation <- function(df){
  
  # ============================================================================
  # 1. Transformation of Variables related to pay_amt
  # ============================================================================
  for (n in c(3,6)) {
    v <- paste0("avg_pay_amt_",n,"m")
    df[[paste0("log_",v)]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]>=1000,log(df[[v]]),log(1000))
    df[[paste0("pt_log_",v)]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]>=1000,log(df[[v]])**(-2),log(1000)**(-2))
    df[[paste0(v,"_lt_1000")]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]<1000,1,0)
  }
  
  for (n in c(3,6)) {
    v <- paste0("max_pay_amt_",n,"m")
    df[[paste0("log_",v)]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]>=2500,log(df[[v]]),2500)
    df[[paste0("pt_log_",v)]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]>=2500,log(df[[v]])**(-3),log(2500)**(-3))
    df[[paste0(v,"_lt_2500")]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]<2500,1,0)
  }
  
  for (n in c(3,6)) {
    v <- paste0("min_pay_amt_",n,"m")
    df[[paste0(v,"_eq_0")]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]==0,1,0)
  }
  
  # ============================================================================
  # 2. Transformation of Variables related to utilization
  # ============================================================================
  
  for (n in c(3,6)) {
    v <- paste0("avg_util_",n,"m")
    df[[paste0("floored_",v)]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]>=0.025,df[[v]],0.025)
    df[[paste0(v,"_lt_2.5")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]<0.025,1,0)
  }
  
  for (n in c(3,6)) {
    v <- paste0("max_util_",n,"m")
    df[[paste0("floored_",v)]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]>=0.025,df[[v]],0.025)
    df[[paste0(v,"_lt_2.5")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]<0.025,1,0)
  }
  
  for (n in c(3,6)) {
    v <- paste0("min_util_",n,"m")
    df[[paste0("pt_",v)]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]>=0.025,df[[v]]**0.5,0.025**0.5)
    df[[paste0(v,"_eq_0")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]==0,1,0)
    df[[paste0(v,"_lt_0")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]<0,1,0)
  }
  
  # ============================================================================
  # 3. Transformation of Limit Balance
  # ============================================================================
  
  df[["log_limit_bal"]] <- ifelse(df$limit_bal>=0,log(df$limit_bal),log(1000))
  
  # ============================================================================
  # 4. Transformation of Variables Based on Worst_status
  # ============================================================================
  
  for (n in c(1,3,6)) {
    v <- paste0("worst_status_",n,"m")
    df[[paste0(v,"_ge_2")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]>=2,1,0)
    df[[paste0(v,"_le_0")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]<=0,1,0)
  }
  
  # ============================================================================
  # 5. Transformation of Age, Education, Sex, Marriage
  # ============================================================================
  
  v <- "age"
  df[[paste0(v,"_le_25")]]  <-  ifelse(df[[v]]<=25,1,0)
  df[[paste0(v,"_gt_45")]]  <-  ifelse(df[[v]]>45,1,0)
  
  v<- "education"
  df[[paste0(v,"_others")]] <- ifelse(df[[v]]=="others",1,0)
  df[[paste0(v,"_grad")]]   <- ifelse(df[[v]]=="grad School",1,0)
  
  v<- "sex"
  df[["sex_male"]]          <- ifelse(df[[v]]=="male",1,0)
  
  v<- "marriage"
  df[["if_married"]]        <- ifelse(df[[v]]=="married",1,0)
  
  # ============================================================================
  # 6. Transformation of Variables Based on Count of Months wiht Status >= x
  # ============================================================================
  
  for (n in c(3,5)) {
    v <- paste0("count_months_ge_",n)
    df[[paste0(v,"_eq_0")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]==0,1,0)
  }  
  
  # ============================================================================
  # 6. Transformation of Variables Based on Count of Months wiht Status >= x
  # ============================================================================
  
  for (n in c(1,3)) {
    v <- paste0("months_since_delq_ge_",n)
    df[[paste0(v,"_eq_0")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]==0,1,0)
  } 
  
  for (n in c(2,5)) {
    v <- paste0("months_since_delq_ge_",n)
    df[[paste0(v,"_eq_1")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]==1,1,0)
  }
  
  #  df[["floored_months_since_delq_ge_1"]] <- ifelse(df$months_since_delq_ge_1>=1,
  #                                                   df$months_since_delq_ge_1,1)
  
  # ============================================================================
  # 7. Transformation of Variables Based on Months with utilization lt/gt x%
  # ============================================================================
  
  for (n in c(10,25)) {
    v <- paste0("months_util_lt_",n)
    df[[paste0(v,"_eq_0")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]==0,1,0)
    df[[paste0(v,"_eq_6")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]==6,1,0)
  } 
  
  for (n in c(50)) {
    v <- paste0("months_util_gt_",n)
    df[[paste0(v,"_eq_0")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]==0,1,0)
  }
  
  v <- "util_volatility_6m"
  df[[paste0(v,"eq_0")]]    <-  ifelse(df[[v]]==0,1,0)
  
  v<- "util_coeff_variation_6m"
  df[[paste0(v,"ge_150")]]  <- ifelse(df$util_coeff_variation_6m>=150,1,0)
  df[[paste0("pt_",v)]]     <- ifelse(df$util_coeff_variation_6m<150,df$util_coeff_variation_6m**0.5,150**0.5)
  
  # ============================================================================
  # 8. Transformation of Variables Based on paid_pct (actually proportion)
  # ============================================================================
  
  for (n in c(3,6)) {
    v <- paste0("avg_paid_pct_",n,"m")
    df[[paste0(v,"_le_0")]]   <-  ifelse(df[[v]]<=0,1,0)
    df[[paste0(v,"_ge_0.5")]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]>=0.5,1,0)
    #    df[[paste0("log_",v)]]    <-  ifelse(df[[v]]<=0.5,ifelse(df[[v]]>0,log(df[[v]]),-4),0.5)
  } 
  
  v<- "months_overpayment"
  df[[paste0("capped_5_",v)]] <-  ifelse(df[[v]]<=5,df[[v]],5)
  
  
  return(df)
  
}

6. Logistic Regression

Baseline Model

I performed the following steps to build the initial logistic regression model based on the transformed dataset.

  • Normalized training data using computed scaling factors.
  • Trained logistic regression model on normalized features.
  • Performed stratified 5-fold cross-validation to evaluate thresholds.
  • Tuned threshold for best F1, Precision, Recall, Accuracy, and balance.
  • Preprocessed and normalized test data using training parameters.
  • Predicted on test set using the trained model and optimal threshold.
  • Evaluated model using confusion matrix, ROC AUC, and PR AUC.
  • Plotted ROC and PR curves for visual performance analysis.
df          <- read_csv("Data/train_data.csv", col_names = TRUE, show_col_types = FALSE )
train_data        <- wrangle_data(df)
processed_train   <- FE(train_data)
Transformed_train <- CleanTransformation(processed_train)
modelling_data    <- Transformed_train[, !(names(Transformed_train) %in% unlist(drop_list))]

# Normalization
norm_factors      <- normalizing_factors(modelling_data)
normalized_train  <- normalized_data(modelling_data,norm_factors)

#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Logistic Regression
logit_model <- glm(default ~ ., data = normalized_train, family = binomial)

#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Stratified 5-fold Cross Validaition for deciding optimal threshold
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

folds <- createFolds(normalized_train$default, k = 5)
thresholds <- seq(0.01, 0.99, by = 0.04)

metrics_list <- vector("list", length(thresholds))

for(i in seq_along(thresholds)) {
  
  threshold_metrics <- list(Precision = numeric(5),Recall = numeric(5),
                            F1 = numeric(5),Accuracy = numeric(5)       )
  
  for(fold in seq_along(folds)) {
    cv_train <- normalized_train[-folds[[fold]], ]
    cv_valid <- normalized_train[folds[[fold]], ]

    cv_model <- glm(default ~ ., data = cv_train, family = binomial)

    # Prediction on validation fold
    cv_probs <- predict(cv_model, newdata = cv_valid, type = "response")
    cv_preds <- ifelse(cv_probs >= thresholds[i], 1, 0)

    pred_factor <- factor(cv_preds, levels = c(0, 1))
    true_factor <- factor(cv_valid$default, levels = c(0, 1))
    
    cm          <- caret::confusionMatrix(pred_factor, true_factor, positive = "1")
    
    # Storing all metrics
    threshold_metrics$Precision[fold] <- cm$byClass["Precision"]
    threshold_metrics$Recall[fold] <- cm$byClass["Recall"]
    threshold_metrics$F1[fold] <- cm$byClass["F1"]
    threshold_metrics$Accuracy[fold] <- cm$overall["Accuracy"]
    
  }

  # metrics across folds
  metrics_list[[i]] <- list(
    Threshold = thresholds[i],
    Precision = mean(threshold_metrics$Precision, na.rm = TRUE),
    Recall = mean(threshold_metrics$Recall, na.rm = TRUE),
    F1 = mean(threshold_metrics$F1, na.rm = TRUE),
    Accuracy = mean(threshold_metrics$Accuracy, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
  print(paste0(i*100/length(thresholds),"% Done"))
}

metrics_df <- do.call(rbind, lapply(metrics_list, as.data.frame))
optimal_thresholds <- list(
  Max_F1 = metrics_df$Threshold[which.max(metrics_df$F1)],
  Max_Precision = metrics_df$Threshold[which.max(metrics_df$Precision)],
  Max_Recall = metrics_df$Threshold[which.max(metrics_df$Recall)],
  Balanced = metrics_df$Threshold[which.min(abs(metrics_df$Precision - metrics_df$Recall))],
  Max_Accuracy = metrics_df$Threshold[which.max(metrics_df$Accuracy)]
)

#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Prediction on Test Set
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
df               <- read_csv("Data/test_data.csv", col_names = TRUE, show_col_types = FALSE )
test_data        <- wrangle_data(df)
processed_test   <- FE(test_data)
Transformed_test <- CleanTransformation(processed_test)
prediction_data  <- Transformed_test[, !(names(Transformed_test) %in% unlist(drop_list))]

# Normalization with Normalization Factors obtained from training data
normalized_test  <- normalized_data(prediction_data,norm_factors)
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------


test_probs <- predict(logit_model, newdata = normalized_test, type = "response")
test_preds <- ifelse(test_probs >= optimal_thresholds$Max_F1, 1, 0)

# Confusion matrix metrics
pred_factor <- factor(test_preds, levels = c(0, 1))
true_factor <- factor(normalized_test$default, levels = c(0, 1))
cm          <- caret::confusionMatrix(pred_factor, true_factor, positive = "1")

# ROC and PR curves
roc_obj <- pROC::roc(normalized_test$default, test_probs)
pr_obj <- pr.curve(scores.class0 = test_probs,
                   weights.class0 = as.numeric(normalized_test$default == 1),curve=T)

# Compiling results
results <- data.frame(
  AUC_ROC = roc_obj$auc,
  AUC_PR = pr_obj$auc.integral,
  Precision = cm$byClass["Precision"],
  Recall = cm$byClass["Recall"],
  F1_Score = cm$byClass["F1"],
  Accuracy = cm$overall["Accuracy"],
  Optimal_Threshold = optimal_thresholds$Max_F1
)

print(results)

## Ploting curves
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(roc_obj, main = "ROC Curve")
plot(pr_obj, main = "PR Curve")

LASSO Logistic Regression

Steps:

  • Converted training and test data to matrix format for glmnet compatibility.
  • Trained a Lasso regression model with 5-fold cross-validation using AUC as the metric.
  • selected optimal lambda (max AUC) and a simpler model within 1SE of max AUC.
  • Predicted test probabilities using the best regularized lambda.
  • Applied optimal threshold (0.25) to generate final predictions.
  • Evaluated performance with confusion matrix, ROC AUC, and PR AUC.
  • AUC (ROC): 0.7768, AUC (PR): 0.5518, Precision: 0.5103, Recall: 0.5946, F1 Score: 0.5492, Accuracy: 0.7833.
  • Plotted ROC and PR curves for visual performance assessment.
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# LASSO REGRESSION
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
library(glmnet)
# Converting data to matrix format (required by glmnet)
x_train <- model.matrix(default ~ ., normalized_train)[, -1]  # Removes intercept column
y_train <- normalized_train$default

lasso_cv <- cv.glmnet(x = x_train, 
                      y = y_train,
                      family = "binomial",
                      alpha = 1,  # 1 for Lasso, 0 for Ridge
                      type.measure = "auc",
                      nfolds = 5)


# Lambda that gives maximum AUC
best_lambda <- lasso_cv$lambda.min  

# Or most regularized model within 1SE of max AUC (simpler model)
lambda_1se <- lasso_cv$lambda.1se


x_test <- model.matrix(default ~ ., normalized_test)[, -1]
y_test <- normalized_test$default


# Predict probabilities
test_probs <- predict(lasso_cv, 
                      newx = x_test,
                      s = lambda_1se, 
                      type = "response",
                      exact = TRUE,
                      x=x_train,
                      y=y_train)[, 1]


test_preds <- ifelse(test_probs >= optimal_thresholds$Max_F1, 1, 0)

# Confusion matrix metrics
pred_factor <- factor(test_preds, levels = c(0, 1))
true_factor <- factor(normalized_test$default, levels = c(0, 1))

                   weights.class0 = as.numeric(normalized_test$default == 1),curve=T)

# Compiling results

  AUC_ROC = roc_obj$auc,
  AUC_PR = pr_obj$auc.integral,
  Precision = cm$byClass["Precision"],
  Recall = cm$byClass["Recall"],
  F1_Score = cm$byClass["F1"],
  Accuracy = cm$overall["Accuracy"],
  Optimal_Threshold = optimal_thresholds$Max_F1
)

Conclusion

Findings:

  • I spent a lot time in understanding the features, deriving new features using domain knowledge, from the view of risk management and in Exploratory Data Analysis.
  • I managed to derive some new features such as Worst_Payment_Status_In_Last_6Months, Ever_Missed_Payment or Credit Utilization Variables which have better explanatory power for default rate than any other predictors. (You can explore them in Feature Explorer).
  • There is very least difference in the model performance whatever the approach I adopted.
  • I tried focusing on maximizing F1-score to get best precision and recall and I achieved F1 Score = 0.555
  • For Logistic Regression, I found that stepwise feature selection has given the best results.
  • For Random Forest, I first reduced the number of features by dropping unnecessary features as per my understating and then run LASSO Variable selection (taken 1se estimates) and finally fitted Random Forest.
  • We see that the final model has only 18 features, which makes the model easily explainable.

Future Work:

Due to Time Constraint, I was not able to perform these methods:

  • Segmentwise Modelling: We can segment the training data into low-risk, medium-risk and high-risk segments based on default rate with help of decision tree as shown in the below image. Doing so will result in homogeneous training sets. Segmentwise modelling captures even small patterns while modelling on whole training data captures only the general patterns.

  • Rule-Fit Classifier: In logistic regression, we have not included the interaction terms. With a motivation of including appropriate interaction terms, we look forward to Rule-Fit Classifier. A Rule Fit Classifier is nothing but a regularized (usually via lasso) Linear Model with original predictors and their interactions. The interactions are obtained using decision trees. An interaction in a rule fit classifier is nothing but the decision rule which is used to get to a certain node of the tree. One can use any tree-based ensemble methods to get these interaction terms.

  • Extensive Grid Search for hyper-parameter tuning for Random Forest. (Computationally Intensive)
